1. Environment Setup for TypeScript

This means preparing your system to write and run TypeScript code.
Usually you need Node.js and a code editor like Visual Studio Code.

2. Installing TypeScript

You install TypeScript using npm (Node Package Manager).

Example:

npm install -g typescript

After installing, you can use the tsc command to compile TypeScript.

3. Installing Essential VS Code Extensions

Extensions help improve coding experience such as:

TypeScript support

Error highlighting

Auto completion

Code formatting

4. Setting Up & Compiling a TypeScript Project

To start a TypeScript project:

Initialize config file

tsc --init

Write .ts files

Compile them into JavaScript using:

tsc filename.ts
TypeScript Basics
5. Basic Types

TypeScript provides predefined types to define what kind of data a variable stores.

Examples:

string

number

boolean

Example:

let name: string = "John";

6. Primitive Types

Primitive types are basic data types in TypeScript.

Examples:

string

number

boolean

null

undefined

Example:

let age: number = 22;
7. Arrays

Arrays store multiple values of the same type.

Example:

let numbers: number[] = [1,2,3];
8. Tuples

A tuple is an array with fixed number of elements and fixed types.

Example:

let user: [string, number] = ["Alex", 25];
9. Enums

Enums allow you to define named constant values.

Example:

enum Direction {
  Up,
  Down,
  Left,
  Right
}
10. Any, Unknown, Void

These are special types.

any → can store any value (not type safe)

unknown → similar to any but safer

void → used when a function returns nothing

Example:

function log(): void {
  console.log("Hello");
}
11. Type Inference

TypeScript automatically detects the type of a variable based on its value.

Example:

let name = "John"; 

TypeScript understands it is a string.

12. Type Annotations

Explicitly telling TypeScript what type a variable should be.

Example:

let age: number = 25;
Interfaces & Type Aliases
13. Interfaces

An interface defines the structure of an object.

Example:

interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}
14. Extending Interfaces

Interfaces can inherit properties from other interfaces.

Example:

interface Person {
  name: string;
}

interface Employee extends Person {
  salary: number;
}
15. Type Aliases

A type alias gives a custom name to a type.

Example:

type ID = string | number;
16. Intersection Types

Combines multiple types into one.

Example:

type A = { name: string };
type B = { age: number };

type Person = A & B;
Classes & Objects
17. Classes & Objects

Classes are used to create object-oriented programs.

Example:

class Person {
  name: string;
}
18. Constructor

A constructor is a special function used to initialize objects.

Example:

constructor(name: string) {
  this.name = name;
}
19. this Keyword

this refers to the current object of the class.

Example:

this.name = name;
20. Access Modifiers

They control access to class properties.

Types:

public

private

protected

Example:

private age: number;
21. Optional Properties

Properties that may or may not exist.

Example:

interface User {
  name: string;
  age?: number;
}
22. Parameter Properties

Shortcut to define and initialize properties in constructor.

Example:

constructor(public name: string) {}
23. Getters & Setters

Used to get or update values safely.

Example:

get name() {
  return this._name;
}
24. Static Members

Static properties belong to the class itself, not objects.

Example:

static company = "Google";
25. Abstract Classes

Abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly and are used as base classes.

Example:

abstract class Animal {
  abstract makeSound(): void;
}
Functions
26. Functions

Functions perform a specific task and can have types for parameters and return values.

Example:

function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}
27. Rest Parameters

Used to pass multiple arguments to a function.

Example:

function sum(...numbers: number[]) {}
28. Function Overloading

Allows multiple function definitions with different parameters.

Example:

function add(a: number, b: number): number;
function add(a: string, b: string): string;
Advanced Topics
29. Generics

Generics allow reusable components that work with many types.

Example:

function identity<T>(value: T): T {
  return value;
}
30. Modules

Modules help organize code into separate files.

Example:

export function greet() {}
31. Type Assertions

Used when you want to tell TypeScript the exact type of a value.

Example:

let value = "hello" as string;
32. Type Guards

Type guards help check the type before using a value.

Example:

if (typeof value === "string") {
}